Confirmed — cbm's call graph tracks CALLS at file granularity here (it just lists `kernel/exit.c` as a caller file, matching what you noted), so I verified exact sites directly against source.

## Call sites of `put_task_struct()` in `kernel/exit.c` — exactly 6

| # | Line | Enclosing function |
|---|------|---------------------|
| 1 | `kernel/exit.c:226` | `delayed_put_task_struct()` (RCU callback, line 218) |
| 2 | `kernel/exit.c:521` | `mm_update_next_owner()` (line 446) — early-exit/retry path |
| 3 | `kernel/exit.c:527` | `mm_update_next_owner()` (line 446) — normal-exit path |
| 4 | `kernel/exit.c:1117` | `wait_task_zombie()` (line 1099) |
| 5 | `kernel/exit.c:1310` | `wait_task_stopped()` (line 1259) |
| 6 | `kernel/exit.c:1360` | `wait_task_continued()` (line 1331) |

(Note: line 282, `put_task_struct_rcu_user(p)` inside `release_task()`, calls a *wrapper* function, not `put_task_struct()` directly, so it's excluded from the count — that wrapper itself does the real `put_task_struct` at line 226 via RCU callback.)

## One complete acquire/release pairing — `mm_update_next_owner()`

Evidence, all within the same function (`kernel/exit.c:446-528`):

```
508:	get_task_struct(c);           // acquire reference on candidate new owner `c`
...
513:	task_lock(c);
518:	read_unlock(&tasklist_lock);
519:	if (c->mm != mm) {
520:		task_unlock(c);
521:		put_task_struct(c);    // release: candidate became stale, back out and retry
522:		goto retry;
523:	}
524:	WRITE_ONCE(mm->owner, c);
525:	lru_gen_migrate_mm(mm);
526:	task_unlock(c);
527:	put_task_struct(c);           // release: done using `c`, reference no longer needed
528:	}
```

`get_task_struct(c)` at line 508 takes a reference on the candidate task before dropping `tasklist_lock`, since `task_lock()` alone isn't enough to keep `c` alive across the lock release. The function has two mutually exclusive exit paths after that acquire — the stale-candidate retry (line 521) and the successful-assignment path (line 527) — each balancing the single `get_task_struct` with its own `put_task_struct`. This is a clean, self-contained acquire→release pair, unlike sites like line 226 (`delayed_put_task_struct`) whose matching acquisition is the task's original creation-time reference, not a local `get_task_struct` call.
